---
import BaseLayout from '../../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Connecting Your MCP Server to External Data — AI Agent Puzzle"
  description="A local MCP Server can only act inside one folder. But often the data you want lives elsewhere — weather services, Notion, Google Sheets, government open data. This page explains what an API is, how an MCP Server becomes the bridge, and where to start your first API-based tool."
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container ai-agent-external">
      <a class="back-link" href="/">&larr; Back to Home</a>

      <header class="detail-header">
        <h1 class="detail-title">Letting AI Step Outside the Folder: How an MCP Server Connects to External Data</h1>
        <p class="detail-subtitle">
          We've built a local MCP Server before. It could read class notes inside <code>class_notes</code>, list files, and produce reflection drafts in <code>drafts</code>. That's a great start — we didn't let the AI roam the whole machine, <strong>we narrowed its scope to one designated folder</strong>. But the next problem is around the corner.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          What if the data I want the AI to see<br/>
          <strong>isn't in a folder on my computer?</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        For example:
      </p>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>Weather data</li>
        <li>Government open data</li>
        <li>Notion pages</li>
        <li>Google Sheets</li>
        <li>School systems</li>
        <li>News feeds</li>
        <li>GitHub project data</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        These usually don't sit inside your <code>class_notes</code> folder. They live in external services. That's where we meet something important: <strong>the API</strong>.
      </p>

      <!-- Section: API as a window -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Think of an API as a "Window the Service Opens for Programs"</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        "API" sounds technical, but you can use a very everyday picture:
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          An API is like <strong>a window the external service opens for programs</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        You're not running into someone's system to dig through their files. You follow the rules they publish, <strong>send a request</strong>, and get a response. It's like going to a counter — you can't walk behind the counter and search the filing cabinets. You have to tell the counter:
      </p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>I'd like to <strong>look up this data</strong></li>
        <li>I need it <strong>in this format</strong></li>
        <li>Here's <strong>my identity / authorization</strong></li>
        <li>Please <strong>return the result</strong> to me</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          That's roughly what an API does. It lets programs <strong>talk to an external service in a fixed, predictable way</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: From local to API -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Why the Next Step for an MCP Server Is the API</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The MCP Server we built before looked like this:
      </p>

      <div class="flow-card">
        <div class="flow-step">Gemini CLI</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓ calls a tool</div>
        <div class="flow-step flow-step--accent">Local MCP Server</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓ reads</div>
        <div class="flow-step">Local folder</div>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        For instance, Gemini CLI calls <code>read_note</code>, and the MCP Server goes into <code>class_notes</code> and reads the file. But <strong>if the data lives in an external service, the flow becomes</strong>:
      </p>

      <div class="flow-card flow-card--tall">
        <div class="flow-step">Gemini CLI</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓ calls a tool</div>
        <div class="flow-step flow-step--accent">MCP Server</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓ calls the API</div>
        <div class="flow-step">External service</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓ returns data</div>
        <div class="flow-step flow-step--accent">MCP Server</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓ shapes the result</div>
        <div class="flow-step">Gemini CLI / AI</div>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        In other words, <strong>the MCP Server becomes the bridge in the middle</strong>. On one side, Gemini CLI and the AI. On the other side, the external API.
      </p>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          The AI doesn't need to learn the details of every external service. We can <strong>wrap the API into a clearer tool inside the MCP Server</strong>. The AI sees a simple, focused tool — not a pile of API rules. For example: "look up the weather for a city," "search the course pages in this database," "read the feedback from this sheet."
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: API and MCP relationship -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">How API and MCP Relate</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        API and MCP get conflated easily, so let's separate them clearly:
      </p>

      <ul class="role-list">
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">API</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc">The capability the external service already exposes</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">MCP Server</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc">Wraps that capability into a tool the AI can use</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">Gemini CLI</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc">The workspace where the AI calls those tools</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        For example, Notion has its own API — programs can query databases, read pages, create pages. But <strong>the AI doesn't necessarily want to face the full Notion API directly</strong>. So we can build an MCP Server that wraps Notion's API into a few small, safer tools:
      </p>

      <div class="tool-box">
        <p class="tool-box__label">Tool</p>
        <p class="tool-box__name"><code>search_course_pages</code></p>
        <p class="tool-box__desc">Searches only course-related pages</p>
      </div>

      <div class="tool-box">
        <p class="tool-box__label">Tool</p>
        <p class="tool-box__name"><code>read_course_page</code></p>
        <p class="tool-box__desc">Reads one specific course page</p>
      </div>

      <div class="tool-box">
        <p class="tool-box__label">Tool</p>
        <p class="tool-box__name"><code>create_reflection_page</code></p>
        <p class="tool-box__desc">Creates a new reflection page</p>
      </div>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          Now the AI isn't "managing all of Notion."<br/>
          It's just <strong>using a few classroom-version tools we designed</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        This is the same spirit as the "<strong>classroom-style tool surface</strong>" we talked about before.
      </p>

      <!-- Section: Read API vs Write API -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Not Every API Writes Data — Many Just Read</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        People often hear "API" and think it's dangerous. In fact, APIs come in many shapes.
      </p>

      <div class="boundary-grid">
        <div class="boundary-col boundary-col--can">
          <p class="boundary-label">Read-only APIs</p>
          <ul class="check-list boundary-list">
            <li>Look up the weather</li>
            <li>Look up public data</li>
            <li>Look up what a code stands for</li>
            <li>List existing pages</li>
            <li>Read a single record</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="boundary-col boundary-col--cant">
          <p class="boundary-label">APIs that change data</p>
          <ul class="cross-list boundary-list">
            <li>Create a page</li>
            <li>Update content</li>
            <li>Add a record</li>
            <li>Delete a record</li>
            <li>Send a message</li>
            <li>Publish an article</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The first time you build an API-based MCP Server, <strong>don't start with delete or large-scale modifications</strong>. A good order:
      </p>

      <ol class="reflect-list reflect-list--single">
        <li class="reflect-item">
          <span class="reflect-num">1</span>
          <span class="reflect-text">Start with <strong>queries</strong></span>
        </li>
        <li class="reflect-item">
          <span class="reflect-num">2</span>
          <span class="reflect-text">Then <strong>create drafts</strong></span>
        </li>
        <li class="reflect-item">
          <span class="reflect-num">3</span>
          <span class="reflect-text">Only later consider <strong>updating real data</strong></span>
        </li>
        <li class="reflect-item">
          <span class="reflect-num">4</span>
          <span class="reflect-text"><strong>Delete</strong> usually shouldn't be exposed at first</span>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          Same principle as the local MCP Server:<br/>
          <strong>read first, write later.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: Start from read-only tools -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">For Your First API Tool, Start with a Lookup</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        You don't need to wire up something complex right away. The best first API tool is a <strong>lookup-style tool</strong>: query a piece of public data, search by a keyword, look up the weather for a place, look up what a code means.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">A few advantages:</p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li><strong>Safer</strong>: just reads, won't break the external system</li>
        <li><strong>Easier to observe</strong>: clear input, clear response</li>
        <li><strong>More beginner-friendly</strong>: no need to wrestle with auth, writes, deletes, or sync from day one</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        So your first API MCP tool <strong>shouldn't be named</strong>:
      </p>

      <ul class="cross-list">
        <li><code>manage_everything</code></li>
        <li><code>delete_page</code></li>
        <li><code>update_database</code></li>
        <li><code>send_email</code></li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Better starting choices:
      </p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li><code>search_data</code></li>
        <li><code>get_weather</code></li>
        <li><code>lookup_item</code></li>
        <li><code>read_public_info</code></li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          The goal: get a feel for <strong>how an API gets called, how data comes back, and how the AI organizes the result</strong>. Once those pieces are clear, you can decide whether to add write tools — gradually.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: API responses are not pretty articles -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">API Responses Aren't Pretty Articles</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        When you visit a website, you see a polished page. But when a program calls an API, it usually gets something less polished — <strong>more like a data packet</strong>. A common format is <code>JSON</code>. You don't need to master JSON yet. Think of it as: <strong>a data format that's easy for programs to read</strong>.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">It might look like this:</p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-json">{
  "city": "Taipei",
  "weather": "cloudy",
  "temperature": 24
}</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        To a human, this isn't a natural-sounding description. But to a program, it's clear — city is Taipei, weather is cloudy, temperature is 24. The MCP Server can layer the data into something more readable:
      </p>

      <div class="layer-stack">
        <div class="layer-card layer-card--raw">
          <p class="layer-card__label">API response</p>
          <p class="layer-card__content">
            <code is:raw>{ "city": "Taipei", "weather": "cloudy", "temperature": 24 }</code>
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="layer-arrow">↓ shaped by the MCP Server</div>
        <div class="layer-card">
          <p class="layer-card__label">MCP Server output</p>
          <p class="layer-card__content">
            Taipei is currently cloudy, around 24°C.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="layer-arrow">↓ phrased by the AI</div>
        <div class="layer-card layer-card--ai">
          <p class="layer-card__label">AI natural phrasing</p>
          <p class="layer-card__content">
            Taipei is on the cloudy side right now, around 24°C — fine for going out, but worth keeping an eye on.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          Each piece has a role: <strong>the API supplies data, the AI is good at understanding and rephrasing, and the MCP Server is the bridge in the middle</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: Don't dump raw API to AI -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Don't Dump the Whole Raw API Response on the AI</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        First-timers often pipe the full API response straight to the AI. <strong>That's not always great</strong>. API responses can be long, with many fields the current task doesn't need. Sending it all back can cause:
      </p>

      <ul class="cross-list">
        <li>The AI has a <strong>harder time finding what matters</strong></li>
        <li>The response is too long, <strong>hard to read</strong></li>
        <li>You may end up <strong>exposing data you didn't need to share</strong></li>
        <li>Debugging later <strong>gets messy</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Better: have the MCP tool <strong>shape the data first</strong> and <strong>return only the fields this task needs</strong>. For a weather query, that might just be:
      </p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>City</li>
        <li>Weather condition</li>
        <li>Temperature</li>
        <li>Updated time</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        You don't have to send the whole raw payload to the AI.
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          An MCP tool <strong>doesn't just shuffle data around</strong>;<br/>
          it can also pre-shape the data into a form the AI can use comfortably.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: Basic workflow of API-based MCP Server -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">The Basic Flow of an API-Based MCP Server</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        We'll wrap APIs into MCP tools step by step later. But before writing any code, it helps to picture the whole flow. A simple API-based MCP Server roughly works like this:
      </p>

      <ol class="numbered-list">
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">1</span><span class="numbered-list__text">User <strong>types a request</strong> into Gemini CLI</span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">2</span><span class="numbered-list__text">AI <strong>decides</strong> which tool to use</span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">3</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Gemini CLI <strong>calls</strong> a tool inside the MCP Server</span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">4</span><span class="numbered-list__text">MCP Server <strong>calls the external API</strong></span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">5</span><span class="numbered-list__text">External API <strong>returns data</strong></span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">6</span><span class="numbered-list__text">MCP Server <strong>shapes the data</strong></span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">7</span><span class="numbered-list__text">The tool <strong>returns the result</strong> to Gemini CLI</span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">8</span><span class="numbered-list__text">AI <strong>answers the user</strong> based on the result</span></li>
      </ol>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        For example, the user asks:
      </p>

      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        Please look up the current weather in Taipei and present it in a way that's easy for students to read.
      </blockquote>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">The flow might be:</p>

      <div class="flow-card flow-card--tall">
        <div class="flow-step">Gemini CLI</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="flow-step flow-step--accent">AI decides to call get_weather</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="flow-step">MCP Server calls the weather API</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="flow-step">Weather API returns data</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="flow-step flow-step--accent">MCP Server shapes city, temp, condition</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="flow-step">AI writes a natural sentence</div>
      </div>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          So <strong>the AI isn't answering out of thin air</strong>.<br/>
          It fetches data through a tool, then phrases it for you.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: API Key is next page -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">API Keys Are a Next-Page Topic</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Many APIs aren't open to everyone. They may require an <strong>API key</strong>. You can think of an API key as:
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          <strong>The key for using an external service.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">Some services use the API key to confirm:</p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li><strong>Who you are</strong></li>
        <li>Whether you're <strong>allowed to use</strong> this service</li>
        <li>How many calls you can make <strong>per day</strong></li>
        <li>Whether you can <strong>read certain data</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        We won't tackle API keys here. They tie into <strong>security habits</strong>:
      </p>

      <ul class="cross-list">
        <li>Don't <strong>hard-code API keys</strong> in your program</li>
        <li>Don't <strong>paste them into chat</strong></li>
        <li>Don't <strong>push them to GitHub</strong></li>
        <li>Don't <strong>put them on a public site</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          That whole topic is on the next page. For this page, just remember three things: <strong>some APIs need a key, the key shouldn't be left lying around, and before you actually use a key-protected API, you need to learn how to protect that key.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: Not every external service should be exposed -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Not Every External Service Should Be Wired In Directly</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        APIs are convenient — but that doesn't mean everything should be exposed to the AI. The data below, for instance, <strong>shouldn't be casually handed to the AI</strong>:
      </p>

      <ul class="cross-list">
        <li>Student <strong>personal information</strong></li>
        <li>Unpublished <strong>assignments</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Grade</strong> data</li>
        <li>Private <strong>messages</strong></li>
        <li>Unreleased <strong>interview content</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Sensitive data</strong> outside the course scope</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        So before designing an API-based MCP Server, ask yourself a few questions:
      </p>

      <ol class="reflect-list">
        <li class="reflect-item">
          <span class="reflect-num">1</span>
          <span class="reflect-text">Is this data <strong>public</strong>, or is it <strong>private</strong>?</span>
        </li>
        <li class="reflect-item">
          <span class="reflect-num">2</span>
          <span class="reflect-text">Does the API only <strong>read</strong>, or does it <strong>modify</strong> data?</span>
        </li>
        <li class="reflect-item">
          <span class="reflect-num">3</span>
          <span class="reflect-text">Are students even <strong>authorized</strong> to use this data?</span>
        </li>
        <li class="reflect-item">
          <span class="reflect-num">4</span>
          <span class="reflect-text">Does the AI really need to <strong>see all of it</strong>?</span>
        </li>
        <li class="reflect-item">
          <span class="reflect-num">5</span>
          <span class="reflect-text">Could a <strong>summary or partial fields</strong> be enough?</span>
        </li>
        <li class="reflect-item">
          <span class="reflect-num">6</span>
          <span class="reflect-text">If something goes wrong, could data be <strong>altered or leaked</strong>?</span>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <div class="highlight-card highlight-card--final">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          These questions aren't there to stop you from using APIs.<br/>
          <strong>They're there to help you build tools that are safer and friendlier for beginners.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .ai-agent-external {
    max-width: 52rem;
  }

  .back-link {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .back-link:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  /* Header */
  .detail-header {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-12);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-6);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-title {
    font-size: var(--text-3xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    line-height: 1.3;
  }

  .detail-subtitle {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .detail-subtitle strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Section headings */
  .detail-heading {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-top: var(--space-12);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-2);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-paragraph {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .detail-paragraph strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Inline code */
  :global(.detail-paragraph) code,
  :global(.detail-subtitle) code,
  :global(.check-list) code,
  :global(.cross-list) code,
  :global(.callout-text) code,
  :global(.highlight-text) code,
  :global(.boundary-list) code,
  :global(.reflect-text) code,
  :global(.numbered-list__text) code,
  :global(.layer-card__content) code {
    padding: 0.1em 0.4em;
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
    font-size: 0.9em;
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
    color: var(--color-tag-text);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
  }

  /* Check list */
  .check-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-6);
  }

  .check-list li {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
    position: relative;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .check-list li::before {
    content: '\2713';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .check-list li strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Cross list */
  .cross-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-6);
  }

  .cross-list li {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.9;
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
    position: relative;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .cross-list li::before {
    content: '\2717';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .cross-list li strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Callout card */
  .callout-card {
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-8);
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-8);
